Current focus: <one or two sentences on what you are actively working
toward right now>

Note: any open tracker report whose `note` starts with exactly `NIGHTLY:`
is ALWAYS in scope regardless of what's written above -- that's
`/bug-sweep`'s own explicit hand-off convention for a real bug too big
for a fast sweep (see `bug-sweep.md.template`). You do not need to (and
should not have to) edit this file just to let a flagged bug through.

**Policy: build maximally autonomously.** Anything else sitting in the
tracker (see ../INTAKE.md -- `type=feature` reports ARE the running
feature backlog, there's no separate file for this) is fair game to
actually BUILD, not just analyze and summarize:

- Pick the most reasonable interpretation and build it -- don't wait for
  permission on an ordinary, git-revertible decision.
- A genuinely new/distinct idea (not a continuation of the focus above)
  gets its OWN branch off `main`, named for what it is, pushed on its
  own. Rolling back a bad call is then just not merging it -- that's what
  "make it easy to roll back" means in practice.
- Flag what got built and why in `.claude/QUESTIONS.md` (see
  `QUESTIONS.md.template`) and in the report -- the flag IS the review
  point, not a request to build.
- **The only real stop-and-wait bar: something that can't be reverted.**
  A commit, a branch, a tracker POST, a deploy to a confirmed-safe
  non-production deployment -- none of these block you. What does: a
  real external side effect outside git's own reach (a message to a real
  person, an action against someone else's system, spending real money,
  deleting something with no backup). If genuinely unsure, that's the
  `.claude/QUESTIONS.md` case -- but err toward "revertible, proceed."
